SIMPLE: sure
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sure
<hw>Sure</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Surer</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Surest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sur</ets>, OF.
<ets>se⟦uum⟧r</ets>, F. <ets>s⟦ucir⟧r</ets>, L. <ets>securus</ets>;
<ets>se</ets> aside, without + <ets>cura</ets> care. See
<er>Secure</er>, and cf. <er>Assure</er>, <er>Insure</er>,
<er>Sicker</er> sure.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Certainly knowing and
believing; confident beyond doubt; implicity trusting; unquestioning;
positive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We are <qex>sure</qex> that the judgment of God is according to
truth against them which commit such things.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. ii.
2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'm <qex>sure</qex> care 's an enemy of life.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Certain to find or retain; <as>as, to be
<ex>sure</ex> of game; to be <ex>sure</ex> of success; to be
<ex>sure</ex> of life or health</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Fit or worthy to be depended on; certain not to fail
or disappoint expectation; unfailing; strong; permanent; enduring.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧His <xex>sure</xex> word.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Keble.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord will certainly make my lord a <qex>sure</qex> house;
because my lord fighteth the battles of the Lord.</q> <rj><qau>1 Sam.
xxv. 28.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The testimony of the Lord is <qex>sure</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ps.
xix. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which put in good <qex>sure</qex> leather sacks.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Betrothed; engaged to marry.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king was <qex>sure</qex> to Dame Elizabeth Lucy, and her
husband before God.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I presume . . . that you had been <qex>sure</qex> as fast as faith
could bind you, man and wife.</q> <rj><qau>Brome.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Free from danger; safe; secure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fear not; the forest is not three leagues off;⟦br⟧
If we recover that we are <qex>sure</qex> enough.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <cs><mcol><col><b>To be sure</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Be
sure</b></col></mcol>, <cd>certainly; without doubt; as, Shall you do?
<xex>To be sure</xex> I shall.</cd> -- <col><b>To make sure</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To make certain; to secure so that there can be no
failure of the purpose or object.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Make</xex> Cato
<xex>sure</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Addison.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧A peace can not fail,
provided we <xex>make sure</xex> of Spain.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Sir W.
Temple.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To betroth.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She that's <qex>made sure</qex> to him she loves not well.</q>
<rj><qau>Cotgrave.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Certain; unfailing; infallible; safe; firm;
permanent; steady; stable; strong; secure; indisputable; confident;
positive.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sure</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sure
<hw>Sure</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a sure manner;
safely; certainly.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Great, <xex>sure</xex>, shall be thy
meed.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is pleasant, <qex>sure</qex>, to see one's name in print.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sure-footed</ent>⟦br⟧
